Topics in Artificial Intelligence for Health & Life Science
Navya, Melissa, Reagan, Emily

Executive Summary:
Medical dosing errors are a critical challenge in healthcare, which contributes to approximately 7000-9000 deaths annually in the United States and affecting at least 1.5 million patients per year. The traditional method of one-size fits all dosing doesn’t take into account different patient variability. Our paper presents a precision dosing calculator(Advanced Dosage Estimator) that utilizes patient specific parameters including weight, height, age, and clinical conditions in order to generate personalized medication recommendations (in this case, the amount of dosage of medication). We plan to incorporate pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic principles, body surface area calculations, and machine learning enhanced predictions with confidence scoring. By doing so, our product/system removed the implications and gaps surrounding standardized dosing protocols designed for average patients and care that they require.


Problem & Clinical Significance: 
Limitation of “One Size Fits All” Dosing
The main issue of “One size fits all” dosing is the traditional approach to medication dosing. It relies on standardized protocols which are designed for average patients. This population based method fails to account for the significant variability between the individual patients. Some differences are related to body composition and size because they dramatically affect how drugs are distributed and metabolized. There are also age related factors that affect pediatric, adult, and geriatric populations which process medications at different rates. Another main factor are clinical conditions that affect organ function (particularly the kidney and liver), diseases, etc.

Inadequate Dosing
There are additional consequences of inadequate dosing. For example, when patients receive standardized doses that don’t fit their unique physiological characteristics, it might lead to two drastic problems. If they were underdosed, it might lead to therapeutic failure, disease progression, and potential development of drug resistance. If they were overdosed, it might result in toxic side effects, adverse drug reactions, organ damage, and potentially even death.



Why Precision Dosing is important:
Healthcare providers currently lack accessible, user-friendly tools that can calculate personalized medication dosages at the point of care. While PK/PD principles are well-established in pharmaceutical research, the main problem is in translating these complex models into useful clinical applications. This problem is especially critical in emergency situations, pediatric care, and the treatments of patients with complex past conditions where dosing precision may be more harmful than useful.


Key Concepts:
Personalized Dosing (Precision Medicine)
The act of adapting drug dosages to each patient’s genetic profile and specific biomarkers
Switch away from the “one size fits all” population averages
Produces more benefits and less side effects
Machine Learning for Dosing
AI models will analyze patient data (which include weight, age, genetics, organ function) to predict personalized doses
PKPD Modeling
Stands for Pharmacokinetics and Pharmacodynamics
PK looks at how the body affects the drug
Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, and Excretion 
PD looks at how the drug affects the body and produces desired therapeutic effects

Drug development simulation - anything from biological target identification to drug candidate screening
Precision Medicine and Personalized Therapies:
Idea: Developing drugs and treatment regimens tailored to an individual's unique genetic profile, biomarkers, and disease characteristics. This is especially relevant in oncology (cancer) where a tumor's specific genetic mutations can determine the most effective treatment.
Technology: Advanced DNA sequencing, biomarker identification, and pharmacogenomics.
Dosage and prescription 
Steps: 
Modeling to determine the healthiest dose for human clinical trials. 
Optimization for drug administration
Taking in information regarding special groups of people, ex; pregnancy, children, organ-impared.
Looking Towards The Future: Model precision dosing 



